text: Thing about Wes Anderson is that he's so reliably Wes Anderson. You know what you're getting visually & thematically (as well as who will show up); and yet he lets the stories surprise you with the directions they head in. Anybody hating on his movies for being gimmicky don't see that he's able to pull off wildly surprising & memorable human stories again & again using essentially the same visual canvas. Feel like this would be harder than blowing up & reinventing your style with every picture.

text: I was forced to watch Fantastic Mr. Fox with my little sister, and I have to say, I have never been more glad of a forced viewing. It was one of the most refreshing, happiest, heart-warming movies I have seen in a long time. I then watched Moonrise Kingdom - again with some doubt - because I thought it would be much less entertaining than the brilliant stop-motion movie, but was, again, to my pleasant surprise, proven very wrong. Wes Anderson's quirky style refreshingly paints a beautiful adventure story that is unlike any other film I have ever seen before. As a Wes Anderson fan, I am glad he is doing so well. He has a long and great future ahead of him. I can't wait for this one!

text: I remember when I was a Fahrenheit 451 policeman --Agatha Christie books were the bane of our life. Sometimes they'd catch fire before we even threw them in the flames, because God was so impatient. We crucified the guy who played Poirot, but his little beady eyes wouldn't burn and they just rolled out of the fire and were carried off by Satanic crow, and by the next week he'd already filmed a new episode where he was in a British Colonial Stately Home even more generic than the last, and the Lord of the Manor was played by Ralph Fiennes, who was played by Nigel Havers, and they all had specially fitted springs in their jaws to show they were acting.

text: So far, I have seen five Wes Anderson films (Rushmore, Life Aquatic, Mr. Fox, Moonrise Kingdom and this one.). This one is the ONLY one of his I've truly enjoyed. The rest are ok at best, and I thought Moonrise was awful. But Ralph Fiennes just brings such an infectious charisma to this film that it's impossible for me not to enjoy. The film is delightfully absurd. Anderson can suck all the humor from even the otherwise genius Bill Murray, but not Ralph Fiennes. He alone makes this not only Anderson's best film, but one of the year's best so far. Props to Mr. Fiennes, a drastically underappreciated comic talent.

text: The Grand Budapest Hotel is probably one of the best of the year (probably in the top 10) and lets talk about why that is  The Characters: The main protagonist, M. Gustave, is an incredibly despicable hero. I mean it, everything this character says and does are probably the stupidest and cold-hearted things a person can say in real life. BUT! Thanks to Wes Anderson & Hugo Guinness' screenplay and Anderson's writing, they managed to make him very likable. There are usually main protagonists that you love to hate or just want to smack in the face. Thankfully, he falls into the former category. Another thing that helps is Ralph Fiennes' performance. If you watch this film again, you can see how much Fiennes eats up the part, he's just enjoying every minute of it and it's hard for you not get sucked in and enjoy it along with him. Fiennes is one of those actors who's never played the same character in every film. He's played the Pharaoh of Egypt (The Prince of Egypt), A Serial Killer (Red Dragon), he's even been a f**king Nazi (Schindler's List), HOW THE HELL DID THAT HAPPEN!… Anyways, but they've never been the same character. Tony Revolori as Zero Mustafa is also pretty likable too. I mean, sure he sounds like a Guatemalan version of Jesse Eisenberg, but like I said earlier, the Screenplay and the Writing are what helps the movie. And the friendship between Gustave & Zero is actually very genuine and believable. And the side characters are pretty likable and memorable as well. Saoirse Ronan, Adrian Brody, Willem DaFoe, Edward Norton, Harvey Keitel, Lea Seydoux, HELL, even Jeff Goldblum is likable in this movie, HOW DO YOU MAKE JEFF GOLDBLUM LIKABLE!  The Screenplay and Writing: As I said before, Wes Anderson and Hugo Guinness' screenplay and Anderson's writing are what makes the movie good  The Cinematography: This films cinematography is probably some of the best I've ever seen in a while (and this is coming from a 13 year old). Wes Anderson's typical long angle shots work really well here. And what I like about the film more is that everything is real, the building in the movie is REALLY the building they got, all the people they got are REALLY the people they got, NO CGI AT ALL, and I f**king love that!  The Story: Now the film's story is nothing really new, just the typical "somebody gets killed and the heroes get framed for it and go on an adventure to find the real culprit". HOWEVER! Unlike all those other stories, the killer is never revealed at the end. Yeah, you read right, they never reveal the killer. I guess Anderson & Guinness just decided to leave it to the viewers imagination  If theres only one thing I would nitpick, it's the scene where DaFoe's character kills Goldblum's. The problem I have with the scene is…WHY DIDN'T DAFOE EAT THE FINGERS! After DaFoe finishes killing Goldblum, he picks up Goldblum's fingers (which got cut when Dafoe closed the door on them) and puts them in his pocket. WHY DIDN'T HE EAT THEM! I want to see Willem DaFoe eat dismembered fingers, NOT put them in his POCKET!!!!  But other than that, it's a really good movie. 10/10

text: Apart from being visually STUNNING and beautiful, i really didn't see whats so great with anything else in the movie. I don't mean i didn't like it, i was like ''meh'' to most of it, since (acc. to IMDb ratings and friend's experiences) i really had high expectations. Sorry but jokes (that would be funny 80 years ago) are so predictable and not funny, and enforced on me (LOOK, THIS IS FUNNY, LAUGH!). Its biggest problem is its neither funny, neither serious (it could have been such a great serious movie).Story did seem nice but movie was way to short for me to get a real feeling and to connect with characters. It should have been much longer, effect would be enormously better. Though i did like so much details, like newspaper texts, background details you don't notice unless you pause, Agatha's mexico birthmark (yes i noticed its shape before Ralph mentioned it)...I'm not hating on this movie, but i expected a masterpiece and i got something i would call ''nice little movie'', nice to watch,  but forget you ever watched, after few weeks...

text: I'm not a fan of director Wes Anderson. Someone needs to tell him that movies are not all about style , they need to include some modicum of substance . The Gran Budapest Hotel is nauseatingly stylish. Nearly every scene is symmetrical and looks like an over coloured Polaroid.  The story that is being told get whitewashed in Wes Anderson's over production and like most of his work after 20 miutes i just wanted to get off the ride.  Of course , professional critics loved this. Anderson is one of those directors that can do no wrong in their eyes but for me it's a case of the Emperors new clothes.  Vastly overrated.  4 out of 10

text: I've seen this film at least 50+ times now.  Some things I've noticed that I love:  Zero and the elevator bell hop's expressions while Gustav recites the poem. When deputy covax drops the stack of papers on the table one flies off and lands near the edge. When Mr. Gustav and Zero form a 'sacred blood pact' and Gustav hands the paper over to Zero, Zero fumbles with the paper for a moment and catches it. The clock in the kitchen of Mendle's syncs to the background music when they first introduce Agatha. I love how 'our mutual friends predecessor' steps back into the frame when he is mentioned. 'The author', Jude Law's character, is uninterested in the 'parenthetical domestic drama' of a man chocking to death. Inspector Hankel seems slightly uncomfortable when Gustav tells him regarding his mother "I adore her, send my love." When Gustav kisses the corpse of Madam D, Zero and Plateild exchange glances. Gustav expressing rage after saying 'the one with the clubfoot?'  lots more i cant remember, but this film is filled to the brim with subtle humor and light touches that add to a really wonderful experience
